1044
02:11:57,051 --> 02:12:00,773
that there was not going to be a person to fill the position.

1045
02:12:01,393 --> 02:12:04,996
And I want to add, I do just feel like I need to add in this situation.

1046
02:12:05,136 --> 02:12:12,020
I was at the school committee meeting two years ago when Angela came up to the podium and asked very respectfully what the plan was.

1047
02:12:12,200 --> 02:12:13,981
And it was embarrassing.

1048
02:12:14,001 --> 02:12:18,963
And I think there was only probably one or two other people in the audience, but there were lots of people watching at home.

1049
02:12:19,023 --> 02:12:20,684
And it was embarrassing and humiliating.

1050
02:12:20,724 --> 02:12:23,606
And I felt terribly for Angela in that experience.

1051
02:12:23,626 --> 02:12:25,127
I remember writing an email to

1052
02:12:25,580 --> 02:12:27,061
the school committee after that meeting.

1053
02:12:27,421 --> 02:12:30,824
I actually befriended Angela as a result of that meeting.

1054
02:12:30,984 --> 02:12:34,687
It was entirely unfortunate and it was two years ago.

1055
02:12:34,707 --> 02:12:34,747
Ms.

1056
02:12:36,408 --> 02:12:36,808
Van de Kloot.

1057
02:12:37,609 --> 02:12:44,594
So I understand that that evening was unfortunate and did not play well.

1058
02:12:45,215 --> 02:12:54,542
I think that you meant the question now, you know, in a respectful way and that responded by saying, hey, this is the plan, okay?

1059
02:12:55,193 --> 02:12:58,134
There were extenuating circumstances which happened, okay?

1060
02:12:58,174 --> 02:13:04,376
There's another person who might have been a potential, but it wasn't a good time for her to take the role.

1061
02:13:08,658 --> 02:13:14,060
We need to look at the large picture.

1062
02:13:15,027 --> 02:13:16,547
and determine what was the best course.

1063
02:13:17,207 --> 02:13:19,428
And I understand there are a lot of people who disagree with us.

1064
02:13:20,328 --> 02:13:31,710
The only thing that I can say is that there are five people who are extraordinarily different in many, many ways, and yet five of us agreed that this was the best path.

1065
02:13:32,410 --> 02:13:35,090
Two did not, and I respect my colleagues for their decision.

1066
02:13:36,051 --> 02:13:41,532
But this is the way it operates in our public discourse of majority rules.

1067
02:13:41,912 --> 02:13:43,872
Five of us agreed that this was the best way.

1068
02:13:45,166 --> 02:13:58,977
In going forward, absolutely, especially if we have any changes in the way that we operate at central administration, we'll need to come up with a new succession plan in case we have, and hopefully we won't, hopefully we won't in the future.

1069
02:14:00,138 --> 02:14:08,405
We wish our new superintendent-elect a long and hopefully blissful reign as being superintendent.

1070
02:14:09,686 --> 02:14:10,247
Mr. Russo.

1071
02:14:12,092 --> 02:14:12,432
Thank you.

1072
02:14:13,472 --> 02:14:17,573
So I'm a software developer and have been for 20 years.

1073
02:14:19,194 --> 02:14:33,637
And one of the things that I learned probably a couple of years ago, quite surprisingly in an article, was about 80% of what I write for software, if I'm doing my job correctly, is exception handling, is handling the unexpected.

1074
02:14:34,738 --> 02:14:39,619
And the reason I bring that up is that as a body, when we write policies,

1075
02:14:41,428 --> 02:14:51,870
We have a choice, not sure it's always necessarily a conscious choice, but we have a choice about whether to make the policies robust to handle the unexpected.

1076
02:14:52,971 --> 02:15:06,273
And in software, where literally the entire environment is completely controlled by me, 80% of what I'm writing is to deal with the wild, crazy things that are happening.

1077
02:15:07,013 --> 02:15:09,614
But in a human endeavor, which is everything we're talking about,

1078
02:15:10,628 --> 02:15:17,691
it's probably 99.999% of the possibilities are not within the control of anybody in this room.

1079
02:15:18,571 --> 02:15:37,800
And my point is just that when we write a policy, if we try to write policies that are truly robust and can handle endless scenarios, and the people in this room could write for months and never finish coming up with scenarios for how any policy probably won't work.

1080
02:15:39,177 --> 02:15:56,426
So we can either focus on a single policy for weeks and months and probably years and still never get it right, or we can rely on the fact that we're going to come together when it doesn't work right and then deal with that, maybe make a tweak to the policy and move forward.

1081
02:15:57,206 --> 02:16:00,168
And in my mind, there is just not the bandwidth.

1082
02:16:01,685 --> 02:16:27,377
I don't just mean my personal time, but I mean this meeting to get our policies perfect, or even close to perfect, because that's not a reality, even in situations like my job, where I am in control in a way that is not a reality in the human experience.

1083
02:16:27,844 --> 02:16:35,508
So, you know, do I think it's better to have a one or two page policy that has holes you can drive a truck through if the building burns down?

1084
02:16:36,408 --> 02:16:45,153
Or if, you know, all the superintendent and deputy and everybody with a superintendent license goes to a conference and, you know, they shut down the airlines.

1085
02:16:45,473 --> 02:16:51,976
I mean, we could go on and on for how the policy could be better and more robust.

1086
02:16:53,497 --> 02:16:56,879
But then the simplest of policies would be a book.

1087
02:16:57,990 --> 02:17:02,893
that nobody will read, nobody will know what it says, and you won't be able to use it when you actually need it.

1088
02:17:03,554 --> 02:17:11,499
So I want our policies to be as simple as they can be without, too simple.

1089
02:17:12,179 --> 02:17:20,165
Like, you know, a succession plan that said if we needed a new superintendent for an unfortunate reason was we'd get a new superintendent.

1090
02:17:20,265 --> 02:17:22,706
Like, that's obviously too simple.

1091
02:17:23,087 --> 02:17:24,968
But the number of people in our district that have

1092
02:17:25,489 --> 02:17:33,195
either a superintendent license, or we could use the MASS to get an emergency superintendent.

1093
02:17:33,636 --> 02:17:34,857
I mean, that's good enough for me.

1094
02:17:35,097 --> 02:17:46,226
One pager's plenty, but we can't cover all the scenarios, and so... I definitely don't want all scenarios covered, but I would like the major scenario of...

1095
02:17:47,520 --> 02:17:52,284
If position one cannot be filled, who's going to take control?

1096
02:17:52,784 --> 02:18:04,913
Because right now, this is what there is, and then you're saying tonight that, well, it doesn't really matter because it's not in the deputy or even the assistant superintendent's contracts that they would step up.

1097
02:18:05,733 --> 02:18:10,377
So this, what is on file as the succession plan, is wrong.

1098
02:18:11,437 --> 02:18:12,818
So it can be improved, I agree.

1099
02:18:13,179 --> 02:18:14,039
Or just start over.

1100
02:18:16,088 --> 02:18:16,208
Ms.

1101
02:18:16,228 --> 02:18:19,690
Stone, we have a full agenda as well that we need to get on.

1102
02:18:20,091 --> 02:18:34,379
I just want to say a parent did email the next day and say, you definitely need to put in the new deputy superintendent's contract that they will step in so that we have to add that because that isn't currently in the contract.

1103
02:18:34,419 --> 02:18:42,624
So that doesn't work, which I was a shame on me that I didn't read their contract to know that they did not have to be

1104
02:18:43,974 --> 02:18:47,216
are forced into taking that superintendent's job.

1105
02:18:48,557 --> 02:18:54,420
So that's, we can add that to make sure the next deputy superintendent is their job.

1106
02:18:55,940 --> 02:18:57,701
Final comment, Mr. Benedetto?

1107
02:18:57,721 --> 02:19:02,384
To be clear and transparent, thank you.

1108
02:19:03,104 --> 02:19:03,784
It's been a long night.

1109
02:19:04,625 --> 02:19:07,206
I just want you to know, this didn't come out at that meeting.

1110
02:19:07,626 --> 02:19:07,986
No, it didn't.

1111
02:19:08,066 --> 02:19:10,388
We didn't pull out this paperwork and read the policy.

1112
02:19:11,758 --> 02:19:18,562
Because if we had, we would have went down to the assistant superintendent when the deputy said that she wasn't able to take that position.

1113
02:19:19,903 --> 02:19:24,486
I didn't bring it forward because I was floored by what was being proposed to me at the time.

1114
02:19:24,866 --> 02:19:28,068
It didn't enter my mind until someone asked me for a copy of this.

1115
02:19:28,489 --> 02:19:31,711
And I went, oh my gosh, I can't believe I didn't bring this forward.

1116
02:19:31,971 --> 02:19:35,033
And our new members probably have never seen this or read this.

1117
02:19:35,673 --> 02:19:37,675
So yeah, you're right.

1118
02:19:38,135 --> 02:19:39,416
This should have been implemented.

1119
02:19:39,776 --> 02:19:40,917
I'm surprised it wasn't.

1120
02:19:41,988 --> 02:19:49,553
I would have loved to seen this implemented because I know Mr. Belson wouldn't have left us hanging and he would still be there for vital information.

1121
02:19:49,613 --> 02:19:50,974
And I made that point at that night.

1122
02:19:51,334 --> 02:19:54,576
So I'm being transparent about what I did and what I didn't do.

1123
02:19:54,836 --> 02:19:55,877
I didn't bring this forward.

1124
02:19:55,977 --> 02:19:57,398
I didn't think about this item.

1125
02:19:57,938 --> 02:19:59,219
This should have been implemented.

1126
02:19:59,359 --> 02:20:10,066
This is our policy that we voted on when you brought it forward, when I left you hanging that night, and I apologize for, because I should have said something that evening as well.

1127
02:20:10,520 --> 02:20:14,261
So I own what I've done, and I'm going to try to do better.

1128
02:20:14,841 --> 02:20:17,422
So, you know, that's all I can do.

1129
02:20:18,582 --> 02:20:26,484
And we need to make sure that, you know, we have people like you reminding us, hey, we did this, because we can't remember everything.

1130
02:20:27,064 --> 02:20:27,465
Thank you.

1131
02:20:27,565 --> 02:20:30,485
And thank you for everyone out there tonight that's still here.

1132
02:20:30,605 --> 02:20:35,807
And for folks that are watching at home, we really want to encourage you to remember to come to the school committee meetings.

1133
02:20:36,567 --> 02:20:37,507
Let your voice be heard.

1134
02:20:37,547 --> 02:20:39,488
Your voice matters, and your vote matters.

1135
02:20:39,568 --> 02:20:39,888
Thank you.

1136
02:20:40,248 --> 02:20:41,008
Thank you very much.

